These lists give the [[U.S. state|state]]s of primary affiliation and of birth for each [[President of the United States|President]] of the [[United States]].

==Birth places==
Twenty-one states claim the distinction of being the birthplace of a president. One president's ''birth state'' is in dispute; North and South Carolina (British colonies at the time) both lay claim to Andrew Jackson, who was born in 1767, in the [[Waxhaws|Waxhaw region]] along their common border. Jackson himself considered South Carolina as his birth state.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/03/06/AR2011030603406.html?wprss=rss_print/asection|title=Old fight lingers over Old Hickory's roots|last=Collings|first=Jeffrey|date=March 7, 2011|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|publisher=The Washington Post Company|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref> Born on December 5, 1782, [[Martin Van Buren]] was the first president born an [[American citizen]] (and not a [[British subject]]).<ref>{{cite web| last=Glass| first=Andrew| date=July 21, 2014| title=Van Buren slips into coma, July 21, 1862| publisher=Politico| location=Arlington County, Virginia| url=https://www.politico.com/story/2014/07/this-day-in-politics-martin-van-buren-coma-109149| accessdate=January 6, 2018}}</ref> 

The term [[Virginia dynasty]] is sometimes used to describe the fact that four of the first five U.S. presidents were from Virginia. The number of presidents born per state, counting Jackson as being from South Carolina, are:
* One: [[Arkansas]], [[California]], [[Connecticut]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Hawaii]], [[Illinois]], [[Iowa]], [[Kentucky]], [[Missouri]], [[Nebraska]], [[New Hampshire]], [[New Jersey]], [[Pennsylvania]], and [[South Carolina]]
* Two: [[North Carolina]], [[Texas]], and [[Vermont]]
* Four: [[Massachusetts]]
* Five: [[New York (state)|New York]]
* Seven: [[Ohio]]
* Eight: [[Virginia]]

