== Presidential birthplace and early childhood historic sites ==
The birthplaces and early childhood residences of many U.S. presidents have been preserved or replicated. In instances where a physical structure is absent, a monument or roadside marker has been erected to denote the site's historic significance. All sites in the table below are listed in the [[National Register of Historic Places]].

A dramatic shift in childbirth from home to hospital occurred in the United States in the early 20th century (mid–1920s to 1940).<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Thomasson|first1=Melissa A.|last2=Treber|first2=Jaret|date=January 2008|title=From home to hospital: The evolution of childbirth in the United States, 1928-1940|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0014498307000241|journal=Explorations in Economic History|location=Amsterdam, Netherlands|publisher=Elsevier|volume=45|issue=1|pages=76–99|accessdate=December 5, 2017|doi=10.1016/j.eeh.2007.07.001}}</ref> Reflective of this trend, all presidents born after [[World War II]] (Bill Clinton and every president since) have been born in a hospital, not a private residence.

